0.1 Introduction

This analysis is conducted in R using R Markdown with Knitr for report generation. The raw data as well as the source code for every table, figure, and calculation is accessible at https://www.github.com/kippjohnson/PMQ/

Much of the actual analysis code is omitted from being embedded in the printout of this report because it’s tedious to look at along with the results. However, it is completely available in the markdown file in the Github repository (ProjectReport.Rmd).

NOTE: I got tired of typing “after correction for multiple testing” in this report. All P-Values which are reported as significant in this text have undergone correction for multiple testing using either the Bonferroni, Tukey honest significant differences method, or Benjami-Hochberg method. I usually use the Bonferroni method (0.05/n tests); in one section it makes more sense to use a more elaborate method (B-H) or Tukey, and it is stated when it is used. Tukey HSD is used following significant ANOVA results.

If you are trying to replicate this report, ensure the following R packages are installed and loaded:

library(knitr) # For report generation, not strictly necessary to run code
library(psych)
library(dunn.test)
library(plyr) # for ddply and mutate function
library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)

R code for reading in the data from the Github Repository (/kippjohnson/PMQ):

rm(list=ls()) #clear memory at start
tmp <- tempfile()
download.file("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kippjohnson/PMQ/master/SurveyResponses.csv", destfile=tmp, method="curl")
infile <- read.csv(tmp,header=TRUE)

0.2.1 EBPAS Statistics

The first step is to compute EBPAS total score, along with its subsets for scores of openness and divergence. Education is not included in the EBPAS. Questions 1-12 excluding 3, 6, 9, and 11 define the EBPAS scale on the survey. 3, 6, 9, and 11 are the education questions. There are a number of people who did not completely fill out the first 12 questions of the survey, and for the analysis they will be dropped because we have a large enough number of respondents without them.

Questions 2, 4, 5, and 8 are ‘divergence’ questions, where the questions have answers which have been formulated to be the inverse of the answering scale. They have been reversed in our analysis.

infile2 <- mutate(infile, total1to12 = Q1+Q2+Q3+Q4+Q5+Q6+Q7+Q8+Q9+Q10+Q11+Q12)
infile3 <- infile2[-which(is.na(infile2$total1to12)),] #drop incompletes

Number of people who did not completely fill out the first 12 questions on the survey: 17

Questions here: Do you agree with my decision to drop 17 individuals from the rest of the study? I think it was the best way to proceed, because we have a large number of responses without them and it makes everything harder and less reliable if we choose to proceed with a large amount of missing data.

0.2.1.1 Initial Cronbach’s Alpha Calculations

For Cronbach’s alpha, we use the alpha() function from the psych package in R. The EBPAS cronbach’s alpha is taken from the literature {0.78} (Overby et al., J Pers. Med. 2014), as was done in the paper from which we are modeling this.

N Mean SD Min Max Range Alpha
EBPAS 195 24.800 3.506 16 36 20 0.780
education 195 10.610 2.490 5 17 12 0.545
divergence 195 9.713 2.561 4 18 14 0.545
openness 195 15.087 2.949 5 20 15 0.814

The Cronbach’s alpha for the combined openness & divergence is 0.6869655.

0.2.1.2 Cronbach’s alpha for different possible 3-question subsets of education

From the education questions 3, 6, 9, and 11, we can make four different possible subsets of three questions: 3, 6, 9; 3, 9, 11; 3, 6, 11; 6, 9, 11. Here, we compute the Cronbach’s alpha for these possible subsets of questions.

Alpha
Questions 3, 9, 9 0.2989356
Questions 3, 9, 11 0.4664165
Questions 3, 6, 11 0.6754773
Questions 6, 9, 11 0.3804348

As you can see, none of these are above 0.70, although the grouping of questions 3, 6, and 11 is close. Apparently question number 9 elicited different responses from the other three educational questions. We we do later find a different association for number 9 with our covariates than we do for questions 3, 6, and 11.

0.2.2 Computing Cronbach’s alpha for questions 18-21, 22-25, and 18-25 combined.

Questions 18-21 ask the subject “How comfortable are you in your knowledge about [various genomic testing concepts].” Questions 22-25 ask the subject “How comfortable are you in your ability to [apply various genomic testing concepts in a clinical setting]”. We can also combine all 8 questions together as a general genomic familiarity category. To see if these sections assessed the same central ability, we can compute Cronbach’s alpha for each of them:

Questions 18-21 Alpha Questions 22-25 Alpha Questions 18-25 (Combined) Alpha
0.9012832 0.9272846 0.9338605

As you can see, the Cronbach’s alpha for these sections are extremely high.

0.3 Data Analysis & Significance Tests

0.3.0.1 Frequencies

Question Response Frequencies: Tables of each question’s (1-25) response frequency. These questions are categorized as:

  • EBPAS & education questions (1-12)
  • Attitudes toward DTC (13-15)
  • Comfort using technology (16, 17)
  • Knowledge of genomic testing concepts (18-21)
  • Ability to understand genomic testing concepts (22-25)

The data is coded as follows:

  • Questions 1-12: 1=not at all, 2=to a slight extent, 3=to a moderate extent, 4=to a great extent, 5=to a very great extent
  • Question 13: 0= no, 1=yes
  • Question 14: 1=would not use, 2=would use, 3=did use
  • Question 15: 1=strongly disagree, 2=disagree, 3=uncertain, 4=agree, 5=strongly agree
  • Questions 16-25: 1=not at all, 2=not very comfortable, 3=neither comfortable nor uncomfortable, 4=comfortable, 5=very comfortable
  • Question 26: 1=23 or younger, 2=24-25, 3=26 or older
  • Question 27: 0=male, 1=female
  • Question 28.1: 0=no, 1=yes
  • Question 28.2: 1=MS1, 2=MS2, 3=MS3, 4=MS4
  • Question 29.1: 0=no, 1=yes
  • Question 29.2: 1=MD/PhD, 2=MD/MPH, 3=MD/MSCR
  • Question 30.1: 0=no, 1=yes, 2=Don’t Know
  • Question 30.2: 1=Clinical, 2=Translational, 3=Basic Science, 4=Don’t Know (multiple answers were allowed here, e.g. clinical and translational = 12)

I have currently omitted the response frequency tables for brevity; they can easily be added back into the report if you want.

0.3.1 EBPAS Collapsed T-Tests

Answers for questions 13-25 were tested for an association with EBPAS Score (Questions 1-12 excluding the education questions) using ANOVA followed by Tukey Honest Signficant Differences if called for. After ANOVA, the answers were collapsed into binary categories and T-tests for association with EBPAS score were performed. ANOVA results are not currently shown.

The R output for each ANOVA and Collapsed T-test is shown below. After the end of the output there is a table summarizing the results in a fashion analagous to Table 6 in Overby et al.

The collapsed T-tests were collapsed by assigning the responses in the first three Likert Groups to one group (For example, “Not At All Comfortable, Not Very Comfortable, and Neither Comfortable nor Uncomfortable” were collapsed to Group 1), and collapsing the remaining Likery Groups to a second group (“Comfortable and Very Comfortable were assigned to Group Two”).

The EBPAS scores totals are approximately normal by visual analysis:

Headings for question 13-25 below are a placeholder in the markdown document in case we want to look at the tests in further detail. Individual results can be shown if needed, but are currently summarized in the below table.

  • On question 19, those who answered “not at all/not very/neither comfortable not uncomfortable” had a significantly lower EBPAS score than those who answered “comfortable or very comfortable” (P=<0.0001)
  • On question 22, those who answered “not at all/not very/neither comfortable not uncomfortable” had a significantly lower EBPAS score than those who answered “comfortable or very comfortable” (P=<0.0004)

  • On question 14, those who answered “not at all/not very/neither comfortable not uncomfortable” had a significantly lower EBPAS score than those who answered “comfortable or very comfortable” (P=<0.04)
  • On question 14, those who answered “not at all/not very/neither comfortable not uncomfortable” had a significantly lower EBPAS score than those who answered “comfortable or very comfortable” (P=<0.02)
  • On question 20, those who answered “not at all/not very/neither comfortable not uncomfortable” had a significantly lower EBPAS score than those who answered “comfortable or very comfortable” (P=<0.04)

0.4 Covariate Analysis

0.4.1 Further EBPAS Analyses (against covariates using ANOVA, Questions 26-31.2)

Because EBPAS score is a vector of integers and is approximately normally distributed, the appropriate test to use here is ANOVA. We are looking now for associations between EBPAS and the covariates.

0.4.1.0.1 Covariate Grouping

We need to create a new grouping from Question 28.2 (Year of medical school). We are just merging the M3 and M4 students into one “clinical” grouping, while coding M1s as “pre-didactic” and M2s as “pre-clinical” as was done in Caroline’s Poster. The new vector we create is called Q28.2c (“c” for collapsed).

infile3$Q28.2c <- infile3$Q28.2
infile3$Q28.2c[infile3$Q28.2c==4] <- 3
clinical_grouping_table <- table(infile3$Q28.2c)

In the study, there are 51 pre-didactic students, 63 pre-clinical students, and 79 clinical students.

0.4.2 Education Question Covariate Analysis

KW test is a non-parametric version of one-way ANOVA appropriate here because of ordinal data. The results are summarized in the table below. Correction was done for multiple testing.

0.4.2.2 Post-Hoc Tests on Significant KW Tests

We use the Dunn test to test for pairwise differences following KW significance tests. This is a non-parametric equivalent to the Tukey test folowing ANOVA. The multiple-comparisons correction here is for family-wise error rate (FWER) using the Benjamini-Hochberg method as implemented in the dunn.test R package.

0.8 Concatenated Question 9 Analysis

We first wanted to do a collapsed t-test testing for an association between the openness/divergence components of EBPAS with question 9.

0.8.1 Collapsed t-test for EBPAS ~ Question 9

## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  infile3$EBPAS by infile3$Q9c
## t = -4.0953, df = 62.715, p-value = 0.000123
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -3.621277 -1.246003
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 1 mean in group 2 
##        22.87805        25.31169
Q9 Response Bin N Responses EBPAS Mean EBPAS SD
1 41 22.87805 3.385226
2 154 25.31169 3.367510

We see that there is a significant difference (P=1.229687510^{-4}) for the combined openness/divergence subsets of EBPAS depending upon how respondents answered question 9.

On this question, those who answered question 9 as “Not at all/To a slight extent/To a moderate extent” has significantly lower scores than those who answered question 9 as “To a great extent/To a very great extent”.
